definition.value: A determination of the number of lymphocyte in a blood sample.
A procedure by which biological material is obtained from a subject for testing, diagnostic, treatment, or research purposes.
Measuring a person's own body temperature usually at home using any of a number of types of thermometers.

A characteristic that can be objectively measured and serves as an indicator for the inflammatory response.  It could be used to indicate the normal inflammatory processes, pathogenic processes, state of health or disease, the risk for disease development and/or prognosis, or responsiveness to a particular therapeutic intervention.

value.value: Assay based assessment of a serum sample for detection and concentration (mg/L) C-reactive protein.

C-reactive protein (CRP) measurement is a measurement of the level of C-reactive protein in the blood. Levels are known to rise in response to inflammation, CRP is therefore used as a clinical measure of inflammation. The measurement is used in the process of clinical diagnosis as high levels of CRP are associated with cardiovascular disease, diabetes and hypertension and in some cancers.

definition.value: Detection of circultating interleukin-6, which stimulates the inflammatory and auto-immune processes in many diseases.

value.value: A quantification of interleukin-6, a pro-inflammatory and anti-inflammatory cytokine.

definition.value: A chemokine that can be objectively measured and serves as an indicator for the inflammatory response.

value.value: Cytokines are small, nonstructural proteins, including interleukins, chemokines, interferons, and tumor necrosis factors, which have a multitude of pleiotropic effects in various organs [1]. They are released in a number of paracrine, autocrine, or endocrine pathways and have been implicated in a variety of infections and immune system-affecting disorders by both proinflammatory and anti-inflammatory mechanisms.

Macrophages and T lymphocytes (T-cells) are the primary producers of cytokines which may have predominantly pro-inflammatory (inflammation-promoting)(IL-1alpha, IL-1beta, IL-2, IL-6, Il-8, IL-12, TNF-alpha, IFN-gamma) or anti-inflammatory (inflammation-suppressive)(IL-4, IL-5, IL-10, TGF-beta) abilities.

definition.value: Detection of interleukin-1 beta levels, an IL-1 cytokine family protein, secreted by macrophages and a mediator of inflammatory response.
Detection of interleukin-1 alpha, a mediator of the inflammatory response.
Detection of interleukin-2, a mediator of inflammatory response.
Detection of interleukin-8 levels, a mediator of inflammatory response.
Detection of interleukin-12 levels, an inflammatory cytokine.
Detection of TNF-alpha levels, a cytokine involved in systemic inflammation.
Detection of interferon-gamma, a cytokine that indicates an inflammatory response.
Detection of interleukin-4, a cytokine identified as an inflammation suppressant.
Detection of interleukin-5, a cytokine identified as an inflammation suppressant.
Detection of interleukin-10, a cytokine identified as an inflammation suppressant.
Detection of tumor necrosis factor-beta (TNF-beta), a cytokine identified as an inflammation suppressant.
Detection of serum levels of amyloid A (SAA) in response to inflammation.
A clinical laboratory procedure designed for the quantification of an organic or inorganic chemical within a biological specimen required for diagnostics or monitoring of treatments.

value.value: A quantitative measurement for assessing the amount of glucose present in a blood sample.

definition.value: Glucose Plasma Concentration (GPC) measurement is an essential diagnostic modality for different types of carbohydrate metabolism derangements including diabetes mellitus.

value.value: Glucose Plasma Concentration (GPC) measurement is an essential diagnostic modality for different types of carbohydrate metabolism derangements including diabetes mellitus. The disordered carbohydrate metabolism that underlies diabetes manifests as hyperglycemia. Plasma glucose concentrations in healthy individuals vary with age. Normal fasting plasma glucose intervals (in the morning after an overnight fast) in children are 3.3 - 5.6 mmol/L (60-100 mg/dL); adult range - 4.1- 5.9 mmol/L (74-106 mg/dL). GPCs are approximately 11% higher than whole blood if the hematocrit is normal. Glucose concentrations in heparinized plasma are reported to be 5% lower than in serum.

A quantitative measurement of the amount of glucose present in a sample of blood, obtained from a source that has abstained from nutrition, typically at least 8 hours prior to the sample collection time.
A technique to collect sputum by inhaling hypertonic saline through an oxygen mask in order to induce sputum.
A method of examining structures within the body by scanning them with X rays and using a computer to construct a series of cross-sectional scans along a single axis.

definition.value: Use of a drug that lower the level of glucose in the blood.

value.value: Treatment of retroviral infections with medications that target the virus directly, limiting the ability of infected cells to produce new virus particles.
The process of gathering information regarding a person's medical history.

definition.value: Determination if a patient's background or demographic characteristics makes the patient susceptible to disease.
Determination if patient's travel history may impact current health.
A questionnaire designed to determine if patient's travel history may impact current health.
Determination if the patient may have been exposed to something which would impact the health of the patient.
A test that measures the amount of oxygen and carbon dioxide in the blood. It may also be used to determine the pH of the blood.

value.value: pH and blood gas measurements are used to detect and monitor ventilation, oxygenation, and acid-base disturbances.
The determination of the unmeasured anions (those other than the chloride and bicarbonate anions) present in a sample.

definition.value: A quantitative measurement of the amount of calcium present in a sample, usually serum or urine.
A quantitative measurement of the amount of an electrolyte present in urine or serum.
A quantitative measurement of the amount of an electrolyte present in serum.
A quantitative measurement of the amount of an electrolyte present in urine.

value.value: Any laboratory procedure for growing microorganisms.

definition.value: A type of mechanical ventilation using endotracheal intubation.

value.value: A time-triggered, pressure-limited, inverse-ratio mode of ventilation that provides continuous distending airway pressure with intermittent release phases

label.value: clinical nucleic acid testing for pathogens

definition.value: A technique that detects a particular nucleic acid sequence in order to identify a pathogen (organism or virus) in blood, tissue, urine, or other bodily fluids.

A  tecnique that uses an amplification of nucleic acids  to detect a pathogen.  Some amplification methods include polymerase chain reaction (PCR), strand displacement assay (SDA), or transcription mediated assay (TMA) to detect a virus, bacteria or other pathogen.

value.value: Any of various amplification and detection strategies applied to detection of virus contamination in donor blood. Specifically designed to detect recently infected individuals during the latency period before seroconversion.

A type of nucleic acid amplification test in which sample DNA is exposed to a single temperature in the presence of multiple sets of primers and a polymerase with replication and high strand displacement activity. This test negates the need for thermal cyclers and may be a low cost alternative to PCR.

definition.value: A technique that detects a particular DNA sequence in order to identify a pathogen (organism or virus) in blood, tissue, urine, or other bodily fluids.
A technique that detects a particular RNA sequence in order to identify a pathogen (organism or virus) in blood, tissue, urine, or other bodily fluids.

A clinical assay that amplifies and quantifies a specific DNA molecule based on in tissue, blood, sputum, urine, or any other bodily fluid to detect the presence of a pathogen.  It enables both detection and quantification of one or more specific sequences in a DNA sample.

label.value: clinical quantitative reverse transcription PCR testing

definition.value: A method to measure very small amounts of RNA transcripts as cDNA targets from tissue, blood, sputum or other body fluids.
A procedure producing an image on a radiosensitive surface by x-ray radiation that has penetrated and passed through a structure in order to diagnose or treat a patient.

The process of taking a thorough history and physical exam to determine if a patient has been exposed to an infectious disease.  Close attention is paid to travel history, environmental exposures, and vaccination history.
